<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-063-044  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 063 044.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Feb 1989 v18 n2 p131(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High-flying Hughes earns its wide area networking wings. (includesrelated article on EDEN network architecture)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Covert, Jack; Nakamura, Tom; Niccolai, Nilo A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Hughes Aircraft Co's Engineering Design Network (EDEN) is ahigh-speed wide area network (WAN) that supports the Ethernetphysical transmission protocol and the DECnet, TCP-IP and XNShigher-level protocols.andP;  EDEN is said to be the world's largestfully Ethernet-based WAN, interconnecting 12 design centers andover 2,000 individual nodes.andP;  Designed to support the rapidcomputer-aided design file transfers required in very large-scaleintegrated chip design, EDEN provides design groups with a sharedcentral computing hub and high-speed transfer over a reliablenetwork.andP;  Five of the 12 connections in the EDEN network currentlyprovide 1.544M-bps T1 speed, linked by Vitalink bridges.andP;  Hughesplans to use fiber optic links to provide higher line speeds inthe future.andP;  The EDEN network architecture is discussed at length.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hughes Aircraft Co. (automation).andO;Topic:     Computer-aided designWide Area NetworksEthernetFile TransferNetwork ArchitectureData Transfer RateProtocolAutomation.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Hughes's engineering design network. (chart)How protocols in the EDEN network correspond to the OSI model.andO;(table)The Missile Systems Group's Ethernet LAN. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>